			<h3 ><a href="#p976">Re: Collision Component / Trigger Component</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=976&amp;sid=a8463ede43783c737354840a82a9a968#p976"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Mensagem" title="Mensagem" /></a>por <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=97&amp;sid=a8463ede43783c737354840a82a9a968" style="color: #000066;" class="username-coloured">thelinuxlich</a></strong> &raquo; 20 Jun 2011, 14:06 </p>

			

			<div class="content">As Thiago said, this has to be well thought. The Entity System paradigm doesn't blend well with the Evented model aka &quot;Components talking to each other directly&quot; (at least, from what I've seen in a lot of implementations, people give up in the middle of the way 'cause the thing start to look like an overcomplicated OOP architecture). <br />The Ploobs messages which feeds the Artemis state should be taken care inside Systems; Components are supposed to hold only data.<br />Remember, Artemis is a clock-driven paradigm.</div>

			

		</div>

		
