		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p991">Re: Collision Component / Trigger Component</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=991&amp;sid=a8463ede43783c737354840a82a9a968#p991"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Mensagem" title="Mensagem" /></a>por <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=54&amp;sid=a8463ede43783c737354840a82a9a968" style="color: #000066;" class="username-coloured">tpastor</a></strong> &raquo; 20 Jun 2011, 20:29 </p>

			

			<div class="content">if the system recieve messages we will have some problems cause we are mixing two paradigms (system process components not messages)<br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div> Because otherwise the component will extend the ireceiver and threat only one method</div></blockquote><br />i think this is ok, it is a stateless simple method<br /><br />components will have a message list maybe, a the entity will process them.<br />a more robust aproach will be all 'ploobs&quot; extend an aditional abstract class that handle messages and store them inside a dictionary (messageType -&gt; messages)<br />and the systems just &quot;process&quot; the stored messages.<br /><br />another stuff. the editor can handle Any type of components or just the registered ones.<br />i was thinking about making some &quot;reflection magic vodoo&quot; to handle all the componets in a single interface.<br />you could load them in runtime (load a dll, search for classes that extends Component and list them. the user could choose one and add to the current entity)<br />He would also capable of changing the components itens (bind the created componente to the property tree (or wherever the name of that wpf component...))<br />i think it is not hard to build a system like this, and worth the effort =P</div>

			<div id="sig991" class="signature">PloobsEngine<br />Creator and Developer<br />ploobs.com.br/?page_id=1381</div>

